04:46.000 --> 04:48.000
Management Analysis

04:49.000 --> 04:54.000
So, management analysis. What is management analysis?

04:54.000 --> 05:00.000
Any manager makes decisions during his or her activities.

05:00.000 --> 05:06.000
These decisions can be based on various factors.

05:07.000 --> 05:23.000
These decisions can be based on emotions, intuition, on someone's order, a wish, on a tradition.

05:23.000 --> 05:30.000
All these types of decisions are present in business, and you all know about it very well.

05:30.000 --> 05:37.000
But among all types of decisions, there is only one type of decision that is considered reasonable and rational.

05:37.000 --> 05:45.000
These decisions are based on accurate information that the management system gives.

05:45.000 --> 05:52.000
This is exactly what is necessary for every modern company today.

05:52.000 --> 05:59.000
And it is necessary for the decisions to be exactly as they should be.

05:59.000 --> 06:03.000
These decisions should be based on information.

06:03.000 --> 06:06.000
These are rational and reasonable decisions.

06:06.000 --> 06:12.000
Management analysis allows companies to focus on their core competencies.

06:12.000 --> 06:14.000
What are these core competencies?

06:14.000 --> 06:18.000
These are the things that companies can do better than others.

06:18.000 --> 06:22.000
The things that other companies cannot do better than them.

06:23.000 --> 06:32.000
At the same time, companies cannot do what other companies can do.

06:32.000 --> 06:34.000
This is also very important.

06:34.000 --> 06:42.000
Because the price of opportunities lies at the core of all decisions and assessments.

06:42.000 --> 06:48.000
If we do something, we give up some alternatives.

06:49.000 --> 06:53.000
This means that we do not do something else.

06:53.000 --> 07:01.000
Any thing should always be compared to what we could do instead.

07:01.000 --> 07:06.000
So, what does the company put all its efforts on?

07:06.000 --> 07:10.000
What gives the company an advantage over its competitors?

07:11.000 --> 07:21.000
For example, the main competencies of Sony are design and manufacture of electronic devices for consumers.

07:21.000 --> 07:28.000
These devices are smaller in size and better in quality.

07:28.000 --> 07:32.000
Can Sony do something else?

07:32.000 --> 07:35.000
Can Sony melt metal?

07:35.000 --> 07:37.000
Of course, it can.

07:37.000 --> 07:39.000
But what will be the price?

07:39.000 --> 07:45.000
The price will be that Sony will not make electronic devices.

07:45.000 --> 07:53.000
What should Sony do if it needs to focus on its core competencies?

07:53.000 --> 08:01.000
For this, companies need to do what is now called outsourcing.

08:02.000 --> 08:08.000
This means that the functions that a company can give to other companies,

08:08.000 --> 08:15.000
the functions that can be performed much better and cheaper by other companies,

08:15.000 --> 08:17.000
should not be performed.

08:17.000 --> 08:21.000
It is better to specialize in what you can do best.

08:21.000 --> 08:27.000
So, outsourcing is the attraction of third parties or other companies to perform the work

08:27.000 --> 08:32.000
that is necessary to carry out the process or service of the function

08:32.000 --> 08:35.000
that is not part of the company's core competencies.

08:35.000 --> 08:43.000
For example, the core competencies of Nike are design and marketing of sports shoes.

08:43.000 --> 08:46.000
The company does not make the shoes itself,

08:46.000 --> 08:49.000
but attracts third parties to make the work,

08:49.000 --> 08:53.000
by contacting the company that specializes in the production of shoes.

08:53.000 --> 09:00.000
We know that Nike is active in a lot of countries around the world.

09:00.000 --> 09:10.000
Recently, Nike has moved production to countries with cheaper labor.

09:10.000 --> 09:16.000
For example, it is already widely known that Nike has its own enterprises in Vietnam,

09:16.000 --> 09:20.000
where labor prices are cheaper than in China.

09:21.000 --> 09:25.000
This allows Nike to maintain the quality of production,

09:25.000 --> 09:28.000
to maintain the design and, at the same time,

09:28.000 --> 09:31.000
to use the advantages of international labor division

09:31.000 --> 09:38.000
and to market its production in countries where labor is much cheaper

09:38.000 --> 09:43.000
and where production is much cheaper and there are fewer other problems,

09:43.000 --> 09:46.000
including with local governments.

09:47.000 --> 09:54.000
Let's look at an example at a specific factory,

09:54.000 --> 09:59.000
at a specific company that allows you to determine

09:59.000 --> 10:06.000
how to carry out the activity,

10:06.000 --> 10:15.000
what to do and what is best to pass on to other companies as outsourcing.

10:15.000 --> 10:19.000
We will use the example of a company.

10:19.000 --> 10:22.000
This company is fictional,

10:22.000 --> 10:31.000
and the people mentioned in this example, as well as in other examples, do not exist.

10:31.000 --> 10:35.000
If there are any coincidences, they can be accidental.

10:35.000 --> 10:39.000
So, we use such a fictional example.

10:40.000 --> 10:48.000
Evgeny Stibelsky is the owner of a chocolate company named after him.

10:48.000 --> 10:51.000
He is interested in knowing,

10:51.000 --> 10:57.000
he is interested in the exact information about the cost of chocolate he produces

10:57.000 --> 11:05.000
and he must determine whether the production and sale of his own brand of chocolate will be profitable

11:05.000 --> 11:08.000
and whether they will remain competitive.

11:08.000 --> 11:19.000
He can design the design, structure, recipe of this product,

11:19.000 --> 11:22.000
he can produce it,

11:22.000 --> 11:30.000
and he can sell the chocolate to a factory that has more competence

11:30.000 --> 11:36.000
and can do it much more cheaply.

11:37.000 --> 11:46.000
So, Evgeny sells chocolate for 1000 rubles per kilogram.

11:50.000 --> 11:53.000
Of course, the numbers are approximate,

11:53.000 --> 11:58.000
they are not related to the current situation.

11:58.000 --> 12:02.000
You know, the numbers can change, the prices can change.

12:02.000 --> 12:04.000
That's why we use the conditional units.

12:04.000 --> 12:11.000
If you know that the prices for this product are at the same level as for other products,

12:11.000 --> 12:13.000
don't think about it.

12:13.000 --> 12:16.000
The number 1000 is convenient for calculation.

12:16.000 --> 12:19.000
That's the only reason why we use this number.

12:21.000 --> 12:30.000
So, Evgeny has an idea about how much chocolate he can sell during the first year of the company.

12:31.000 --> 12:35.000
He gives the task to his accountant, Sergey Chezov,

12:35.000 --> 12:38.000
to analyze the whole chain of creation of cost

12:38.000 --> 12:43.000
and design initial costs per kilogram of product.

12:44.000 --> 12:48.000
So, what did the chief accountant give us?

12:49.000 --> 12:52.000
Let's look at the following table.

12:53.000 --> 13:00.000
These are the estimated costs of making the exclusive chocolate of a new variety, Umka.

13:02.000 --> 13:04.000
The table consists of three columns.

13:04.000 --> 13:09.000
The first column considers the stages of the production process.

13:10.000 --> 13:15.000
The second column considers the initial cost per kilogram

13:15.000 --> 13:20.000
and the second column considers the revised cost.

13:20.000 --> 13:26.000
That is, the cost we can get if we carry out the required measures.

13:26.000 --> 13:29.000
So, the stages of the production process.

13:31.000 --> 13:33.000
Research and development.

13:34.000 --> 13:40.000
The chocolate will cost 25 rubles per kilogram in both cases.

13:41.000 --> 13:44.000
Design work will cost 10 rubles.

13:45.000 --> 13:47.000
Supply will cost 110 rubles.

13:47.000 --> 13:51.000
But in case of revision of the strategy, it will cost only 60 rubles.

13:52.000 --> 13:58.000
Production will be saved from 450 rubles to 350 rubles.

13:59.000 --> 14:03.000
Marketing will be the same, 50 rubles per kilogram.

14:04.000 --> 14:12.000
Distribution and service will be the same, 90 rubles and 65 rubles.

14:13.000 --> 14:19.000
So, the cost in the initial variant per kilogram will be 800 rubles.

14:19.000 --> 14:26.000
The revised cost after the necessary measures will be 650 rubles.

14:26.000 --> 14:29.000
That is, we save 150 rubles.

14:31.000 --> 14:39.000
Of course, the head of the company, Stibelsky, is interested in reducing the initial cost,

14:39.000 --> 14:42.000
which is now 800 rubles.

14:43.000 --> 14:45.000
What does 800 rubles per kilogram mean?

14:46.000 --> 14:53.000
It means that only 200 rubles per kilogram remains to cover all services

14:53.000 --> 14:56.000
for the production of the product and to get the profit.

14:57.000 --> 15:03.000
This difference is the margin, which is 20% of the income.

15:03.000 --> 15:08.000
That is, if we take the price of the product,

15:08.000 --> 15:12.000
calculate the cost, divide it by the price,

15:12.000 --> 15:18.000
1000 rubles minus 800 rubles divided by 1000 rubles

15:18.000 --> 15:23.000
will be 200 divided by 1000, 20%.

15:23.000 --> 15:25.000
Is this a lot?

15:25.000 --> 15:29.000
Evgeny thinks it's not a lot, so something needs to be done.

15:30.000 --> 15:31.000
What does Evgeny think?

15:31.000 --> 15:37.000
The margin should be at least 35% for the enterprise to be successful.

15:38.000 --> 15:40.000
Can we increase the price?

15:40.000 --> 15:45.000
Yes, we can think about it, but the starting price is limited by competition.

15:45.000 --> 15:50.000
Therefore, the only way for Evgeny is to find a way to reduce the costs.

15:51.000 --> 15:53.000
What does the chief accountant tell him?

15:53.000 --> 15:54.000
Sergey.

15:54.000 --> 16:01.000
Sergey says that the highest costs in the chain of production cost

16:01.000 --> 16:07.000
are the costs for the production and supply,

16:07.000 --> 16:11.000
which are related to the production itself.

16:12.000 --> 16:17.000
What are the ways to reduce the cost per kilogram?

16:18.000 --> 16:23.000
The first way is to sell higher volumes.

16:24.000 --> 16:26.000
This product, chocolate.

16:26.000 --> 16:28.000
Is this realistic?

16:28.000 --> 16:30.000
No, it's not realistic.

16:31.000 --> 16:33.000
The next way is to reduce the costs.

16:34.000 --> 16:37.000
Using a single supplier.

16:37.000 --> 16:41.000
Evgeny planned to order materials from many suppliers,

16:41.000 --> 16:47.000
but the orders will not be large enough to get discounts for the volume.

16:47.000 --> 16:51.000
The savings on discounts for the volume is equal to 50 rubles per kilogram.

16:51.000 --> 16:58.000
This is not the biggest advantage that can be used.

16:59.000 --> 17:03.000
The third way is outsourcing.

17:03.000 --> 17:08.000
The company attracts third parties to work on the production of chocolate.

17:08.000 --> 17:11.000
A chocolate manufacturer with a large volume of products

17:11.000 --> 17:15.000
can produce a product at a much lower cost

17:15.000 --> 17:18.000
than the one that could be made at the factory.

17:18.000 --> 17:23.000
The production cost will be 350 rubles per kilogram

17:23.000 --> 17:26.000
versus 450 rubles per kilogram,

17:26.000 --> 17:29.000
if it is produced for 100 rubles,

17:29.000 --> 17:33.000
which is the savings from outsourcing production per kilogram.

17:33.000 --> 17:38.000
That is, 450 rubles minus 350 rubles.

17:39.000 --> 17:43.000
This cost savings would allow the company to sell its chocolate

17:43.000 --> 17:49.000
at a competitive price of 10 rubles and get a 35% discount.

17:50.000 --> 17:52.000
The calculation.

17:52.000 --> 17:58.000
The initial cost for 1 kilogram is 800 rubles.

17:58.000 --> 18:03.000
The cost of changing the cost of using one supplier is 50 rubles.

18:03.000 --> 18:09.000
The cost of reducing the cost of outsourcing production is 100 rubles.

18:09.000 --> 18:14.000
The total cost of outsourcing production is 650 rubles.

18:15.000 --> 18:19.000
Now we are calculating the new margin.

18:19.000 --> 18:25.000
The new margin will be 1000 rubles minus 650 rubles divided by 1000 rubles,

18:25.000 --> 18:31.000
which is 0.35 or 35%.

18:32.000 --> 18:34.000
Conclusions.

18:34.000 --> 18:37.000
Two important conclusions are illustrated by this analysis.

18:37.000 --> 18:40.000
First, the mission of the enterprise.

18:40.000 --> 18:43.000
The enterprise, as a retail seller,

18:43.000 --> 18:48.000
has no production experience in the production of chocolate.

18:48.000 --> 18:51.000
The company should change its mission

18:51.000 --> 18:55.000
and make the main changes in the way it does business.

18:56.000 --> 18:59.000
Often, this is the best policy,

18:59.000 --> 19:03.000
which is to attract third parties to perform the work

19:03.000 --> 19:05.000
of creating a cost chain,

19:05.000 --> 19:10.000
which is not a part of the company's main competence.

19:10.000 --> 19:15.000
Since the company does not have the main competence in the production of chocolate,

19:15.000 --> 19:20.000
it would not be competitive enough to continue working in this area.

19:34.000 --> 19:39.000
Now we will move on to the second part of our lecture,

19:39.000 --> 19:42.000
which is the traceability of costs.

19:42.000 --> 19:47.000
We have already considered the example of what information is needed

19:47.000 --> 19:50.000
to make management decisions.

19:50.000 --> 19:55.000
We have considered the example of reducing costs

19:55.000 --> 19:59.000
in two ways,

20:00.000 --> 20:05.000
by attaching to a single supplier and by outsourcing.

20:05.000 --> 20:10.000
But this is just the beginning of what we have to study.

20:10.000 --> 20:14.000
In order to study the information

20:14.000 --> 20:19.000
necessary for making management decisions in more detail,

20:19.000 --> 20:23.000
it is necessary to consider the essence of costs.

20:23.000 --> 20:28.000
Yes, in our activities, we all face various costs.

20:28.000 --> 20:31.000
These costs are in our personal lives,

20:31.000 --> 20:34.000
in production and in trade.

20:34.000 --> 20:37.000
We all live around costs.

20:37.000 --> 20:41.000
But is it enough to understand their essence?

20:41.000 --> 20:45.000
Is it enough to classify them

20:45.000 --> 20:49.000
so that based on the various classifications and the essence of costs,

20:49.000 --> 20:52.000
we can make the necessary decisions?

20:52.000 --> 20:56.000
Managers track costs on the cost objects

20:56.000 --> 21:00.000
to achieve a fairly accurate measurement of costs.

21:00.000 --> 21:04.000
Cost objects include products or services.

21:04.000 --> 21:09.000
That is, we can, by producing a number of products,

21:09.000 --> 21:15.000
focus on the costs and take into account the costs of each of these products.

21:15.000 --> 21:21.000
That is, if we have five types of cars that we produce,

21:22.000 --> 21:26.000
we can allocate costs for each of these cars.

21:26.000 --> 21:30.000
If we provide services, for example, medical services,

21:30.000 --> 21:35.000
and we carry out five types of various medical services,

21:35.000 --> 21:41.000
then we can allocate costs for each of these types.

21:41.000 --> 21:45.000
The next type of cost object is the sales area.

21:46.000 --> 21:51.000
For example, a company sells goods in Moscow,

21:51.000 --> 22:01.000
St. Petersburg, Yekaterinburg, Krasnodar, Kiev, Minsk, and other cities.

22:01.000 --> 22:10.000
Each of these cities can be classified as a cost.

22:10.000 --> 22:16.000
All costs associated with each of the cities will be considered a cost object.

22:16.000 --> 22:23.000
The next type of cost classification includes departments or units of the organization.

22:23.000 --> 22:25.000
What does this mean?

22:25.000 --> 22:28.000
The organization has several departments.

22:28.000 --> 22:35.000
Production department, sales department, shopping department, marketing department,

22:35.000 --> 22:41.000
personnel management department, finance department, accounting department.

22:41.000 --> 22:46.000
Each of these departments can be classified as a cost,

22:46.000 --> 22:50.000
and each of these departments will be a cost object.

22:50.000 --> 22:54.000
And operational activities.

22:54.000 --> 22:57.000
A company can carry out several types of activities.

22:58.000 --> 23:05.000
For example, a bank can support citizens' deposits,

23:05.000 --> 23:07.000
that is, the so-called retail.

23:07.000 --> 23:10.000
A bank can also engage in investment activities,

23:10.000 --> 23:14.000
can serve corporate clients,

23:14.000 --> 23:22.000
can carry out various procedures related to the maintenance of trust operations.

23:22.000 --> 23:26.000
All of these types of activities can also be a cost object.

23:27.000 --> 23:31.000
Next, we will look at direct and indirect cost measures.

23:31.000 --> 23:33.000
Direct and indirect.

23:33.000 --> 23:34.000
What does this mean?

23:34.000 --> 23:40.000
Direct costs are costs that directly relate to the cost object.

23:40.000 --> 23:45.000
At the same time, indirect costs cannot directly relate to the cost object.

23:45.000 --> 23:55.000
For example, direct costs are labor costs to manufacture a nut in production.

23:55.000 --> 23:59.000
Labor costs are direct costs.

23:59.000 --> 24:06.000
But, for example, the amortization of equipment for the manufacture of the same nut is a direct cost.

24:06.000 --> 24:08.000
A direct cost.

24:08.000 --> 24:14.000
These direct and indirect cost measures are used to support price decisions,

24:14.000 --> 24:16.000
that is, decisions on price determination,

24:16.000 --> 24:22.000
as well as decisions on redistribution of resources to other cost objects.

24:23.000 --> 24:29.000
That is, we either have to distribute resources, or we have to work with prices.

24:29.000 --> 24:31.000
What are direct costs?

24:31.000 --> 24:39.000
Direct costs are costs that can be conveniently and economically traced to the cost object.

24:39.000 --> 24:45.000
For example, the cost object is the flight of the air fleet.

24:46.000 --> 24:52.000
That is, the flight of the air fleet takes off with passengers,

24:52.000 --> 24:58.000
and we consider this flight as a cost object.

24:58.000 --> 25:01.000
One single, separate flight.

25:01.000 --> 25:05.000
What are the direct costs in this flight?

25:06.000 --> 25:08.000
Crew salary.

25:09.000 --> 25:14.000
Crew salary is based on the time spent and tariff estimates,

25:14.000 --> 25:19.000
which are shown on the work time and payment details.

25:19.000 --> 25:21.000
Fuel costs.

25:21.000 --> 25:29.000
Yes, we can say exactly how much the crew will be paid for one flight.

25:29.000 --> 25:38.000
We can also say exactly how much fuel one flight of the aircraft will consume.

25:38.000 --> 25:40.000
What are indirect costs?

25:40.000 --> 25:47.000
Indirect costs are costs that cannot be conveniently and economically traced to the cost object.

25:47.000 --> 25:49.000
Examples.

25:49.000 --> 25:53.000
Nails used to assemble furniture.

25:53.000 --> 25:57.000
Salt used to make cookies.

25:57.000 --> 26:01.000
Rivets used in airplanes.

26:01.000 --> 26:05.000
Also, indirect costs may be aircraft suspension.

26:06.000 --> 26:11.000
These costs must be included in the costs for the product and service.

26:11.000 --> 26:20.000
To be precise, so that we can say exactly how much each action we carry out costs.

26:20.000 --> 26:23.000
How much does each flight of the aircraft cost?

26:23.000 --> 26:26.000
How much does each pack of cookies cost?

26:26.000 --> 26:31.000
How much does each made wardrobe or chair cost?

26:32.000 --> 26:40.000
These indirect costs are also related to the cost of a certain developed formula.

26:40.000 --> 26:49.000
We will talk later how this can be done, because a lot depends on how we distribute these costs.

26:49.000 --> 27:04.000
Knowledge of how these costs are distributed will allow us to make decisions and take into account everything we do.

27:04.000 --> 27:07.000
And to carry out our activities more effectively.

27:07.000 --> 27:11.000
So, costs for the insurance of the air fleet.

27:11.000 --> 27:15.000
A portion of the costs is related to the cost of each flight.

27:15.000 --> 27:24.000
For example, we have made insurance costs that are carried out once a year.

27:24.000 --> 27:29.000
But how many flights does each aircraft carry out during the year?

27:29.000 --> 27:40.000
We must now take the costs carried out completely during the year and divide them by the number of flights.

27:40.000 --> 27:42.000
By the number of flights.

27:42.000 --> 27:47.000
A portion of the costs is related to the cost of each flight.

