All these costs can be directly attributed to the preparation of the report.

28:28.000 --> 28:36.000
For example, it is clear how much paper is needed to print and prepare the tax report.

28:37.000 --> 28:41.000
The computer also takes a certain amount of time.

28:41.000 --> 28:44.000
And we can say how much time the computer takes.

28:44.000 --> 28:47.000
The work of an accountant.

28:47.000 --> 28:57.000
The accountant spends a certain amount of time and we can accurately estimate how much time the accountant will spend to prepare the tax report.

28:57.000 --> 29:06.000
But there are also indirect costs that cannot be directly attributed to the tax report.

29:06.000 --> 29:09.000
These are the consumables.

29:09.000 --> 29:18.000
Of course, we can attribute how many cartridges will be used, how many pencils, pens.

29:18.000 --> 29:26.000
But no one will count these pens, pencils, cartridges and other consumables.

29:26.000 --> 29:29.000
Because there is no point in doing this.

29:29.000 --> 29:31.000
Next, the rent of the office.

29:31.000 --> 29:41.000
The rent of the office will not be calculated separately for each separate report or separate document.

29:42.000 --> 29:57.000
The utility services, the payment of utilities, electricity, heating, water and other services will not be attributed separately to each tax report.

29:57.000 --> 30:00.000
Just like the amortization of office furniture.

30:00.000 --> 30:15.000
All these expenses have no sense to be attributed to each separately produced product, whether it is a tax report or a car for the automotive industry.

30:15.000 --> 30:18.000
The organization of retail trade.

30:18.000 --> 30:23.000
What types of costs are there?

30:23.000 --> 30:28.000
The cost of shoes.

30:28.000 --> 30:30.000
Direct costs.

30:30.000 --> 30:35.000
The cost of shoes and the salary of the workers in the shoe department.

30:35.000 --> 30:41.000
We can say exactly how much it is necessary to spend to buy shoes for sale.

30:41.000 --> 30:49.000
And we know exactly how much salary will be paid to the workers who work in this department.

30:49.000 --> 31:06.000
But indirect costs such as insurance, utility services, taxes, shoe storage, goods care will not be considered separately for each separately produced product.

31:06.000 --> 31:14.000
That is what separates indirect costs from direct costs.

31:14.000 --> 31:24.000
In a production organization, the cost of production is the direct costs.

31:24.000 --> 31:27.000
These are costs for labor and materials.

31:27.000 --> 31:36.000
In order to produce a product, several consecutive operations are needed.

31:36.000 --> 31:41.000
Each operation requires labor and materials.

31:41.000 --> 31:48.000
We can say exactly how much labor and materials are needed for each production.

31:48.000 --> 32:01.000
How much labor is needed to assemble a car, to assemble all the parts that are included in its composition, to fit and to fix it.

32:01.000 --> 32:05.000
We can also say how much material costs are.

32:05.000 --> 32:11.000
But there are indirect costs that are used when making the same cars.

32:11.000 --> 32:26.000
That is utility services, amortization of equipment and machines, insurance, taxes, effort to control the quality, management, maintenance and operation of equipment, storage and handling of materials.

32:26.000 --> 32:29.000
All of this is indirect costs.

32:30.000 --> 32:36.000
We have learned that direct costs can be direct and indirect.

32:36.000 --> 32:43.000
Direct costs are costs that can be directly attributed to the cost of the product.

32:43.000 --> 32:49.000
Indirect costs are costs that can be attributed but are not necessary.

32:49.000 --> 32:54.000
Therefore, they are never attributed to the cost of the product.

32:54.000 --> 32:57.000
There is no point in doing this.

32:57.000 --> 33:07.000
Efforts to attribute these costs to the cost of the product will not cost the economy that we will get from what we have done.

33:07.000 --> 33:32.000
Let's move on to a very interesting and necessary topic related to decision-making.

33:32.000 --> 33:35.000
This is the analysis of production profitability.

33:35.000 --> 33:46.000
The task is to determine the concept of the dynamics of costs and explain how the manager uses this concept in the management cycle.

33:47.000 --> 33:51.000
Here we introduce a new term, the dynamics of costs.

33:51.000 --> 34:02.000
That is, not just how the costs are divided, but how they change with the change in the volume of production and the volume of sales.

34:02.000 --> 34:05.000
The dynamics of costs are very important.

34:05.000 --> 34:10.000
The dynamics of costs are an important factor in decision-making.

34:10.000 --> 34:19.000
The dynamics of costs are used in the analysis of alternatives and in decision-making.

34:19.000 --> 34:28.000
The best decision will bring more profits for the business owner, better liquidity for creditors.

34:28.000 --> 34:32.000
So, what is the dynamics of costs?

34:41.000 --> 34:51.000
The answer is that the dynamics of costs are how the costs change with the change in the volume of production.

34:52.000 --> 35:00.000
Now that we know what the dynamics of costs are, how they change with the change in the volume of production and sales,

35:00.000 --> 35:11.000
let's define the variable, constant, mixed costs and divide the mixed costs into their constant variable components.

35:11.000 --> 35:14.000
How can we observe the dynamics of costs?

35:15.000 --> 35:19.000
It is always related to the production of products and services.

35:19.000 --> 35:25.000
It manifests itself in commercial, administrative and general economic activities.

35:26.000 --> 35:32.000
If managers can predict the dynamics of costs, the costs become manageable.

35:33.000 --> 35:44.000
There is an old story, a legend, where this idea came from, the idea of analyzing the dynamics of costs.

35:44.000 --> 35:52.000
It was once believed that if you start your business, you need to get support from a banker.

35:53.000 --> 36:10.000
It used to be done by inviting a banker to a restaurant and explaining how the business would work and why the banker should give money for the development of the business.

36:11.000 --> 36:25.000
So, at the most important moment, you need to explain in three simple words why this business will pay itself.

36:25.000 --> 36:27.000
What is at hand?

36:27.000 --> 36:29.000
Nothing.

36:29.000 --> 36:39.000
The restaurant's table, the tablecloth, the food, and a box of napkins.

36:39.000 --> 36:45.000
You take a napkin and make a business plan on it.

36:46.000 --> 36:48.000
How many napkins can you put on it?

36:48.000 --> 36:50.000
Only three numbers.

36:51.000 --> 36:59.000
Three numbers are variable costs, constant costs, and the number of products.

36:59.000 --> 37:11.000
Using these three numbers, you can convince a banker to give money for the development of the business.

37:11.000 --> 37:20.000
Of course, it is more like a legend, a fairy tale, but there is a lot of rationality in it.

37:20.000 --> 37:33.000
That's why we use this theory, which is almost a joke, but at the same time it has a lot of meaning and application.

37:33.000 --> 37:54.000
A modern manager needs to have an idea of what are the constant variable costs, because only then can you determine when the business will pay itself and whether it will pay itself at all.

37:55.000 --> 37:58.000
So, let's make a definition.

37:58.000 --> 38:04.000
Variable costs are those that change with the change of production volume.

38:04.000 --> 38:09.000
Constant costs remain constant with the change of production volume.

38:09.000 --> 38:17.000
That is, no matter how much we produce and sell, the costs will be the same.

38:17.000 --> 38:24.000
Variable costs will change. We sell little, we produce little, the costs are small.

38:24.000 --> 38:30.000
We increase the volume of production and sales, the costs increase.

38:30.000 --> 38:36.000
This division always gives us the opportunity to make decisions.

38:36.000 --> 38:44.000
Mixed costs are those that show characteristics of both constant and variable costs.

38:45.000 --> 38:55.000
Variable costs are costs that change with the change of production volume or other activity.

38:55.000 --> 39:08.000
That is, one product is 1 ruble, two products are 2 rubles, three products are 3 rubles.

39:08.000 --> 39:13.000
This is an example of a direct proportional change in costs.

39:14.000 --> 39:16.000
Let's look at the table.

39:16.000 --> 39:19.000
How do variable costs change?

39:19.000 --> 39:22.000
That is, the dynamics of variable costs.

39:22.000 --> 39:25.000
In this table we see three columns.

39:25.000 --> 39:33.000
The number of produced cars, the total cost of cars and the cost of cars per 1 car in rubles.

39:33.000 --> 39:40.000
I would like to draw your attention to the fact that the prices do not correspond to the real prices that we can observe on the market.

39:40.000 --> 39:42.000
Prices are given conditionally.

39:42.000 --> 39:50.000
For one car, the cost of tires per 1 car is 1920 rubles.

39:50.000 --> 39:57.000
The total cost of tires per 1 car is 1920 rubles.

39:57.000 --> 39:58.000
Why?

39:58.000 --> 40:04.000
The cost of tires per 1 car is multiplied by the number of produced cars.

40:05.000 --> 40:13.000
Next, if we have two cars, we must multiply the number 1920 by 2.

40:13.000 --> 40:16.000
We get 3840.

40:16.000 --> 40:24.000
Next, we multiply by 3, 4, 5, depending on how many cars we have produced.

40:24.000 --> 40:33.000
And for 10 cars, this number will correspond to 19200.

40:33.000 --> 40:38.000
Thus, we see how variable costs change.

40:38.000 --> 40:43.000
They are directly proportional to the number of produced cars.

40:43.000 --> 40:48.000
In this diagram, we see how this is illustrated.

40:48.000 --> 40:56.000
That is, variable costs per unit of production are constant.

40:56.000 --> 41:03.000
The cost of tires per 1 car will be a constant value.

41:03.000 --> 41:14.000
And the total cost of tires is a variable cost, since it changes directly proportional to the number of produced cars.

41:14.000 --> 41:17.000
Now let's look at constant costs.

41:17.000 --> 41:26.000
These are costs that remain unchanged within the range of predictability of the production volume or other activity.

41:26.000 --> 41:32.000
To do this, we must define the concept of the range of predictability.

41:32.000 --> 41:34.000
What is it?

41:34.000 --> 41:40.000
This is the size of the production in which a large-scale base is used to calculate constant costs,

41:40.000 --> 41:46.000
and most likely will be carried out in the current production plan.

41:46.000 --> 41:52.000
Naturally, the dynamics of constant costs are different from the dynamics of variable costs.

41:52.000 --> 42:03.000
According to the economic theory, all costs are variable in the long term.

42:04.000 --> 42:12.000
If we recall the economic theory, we know that there is a short-term approach,

42:12.000 --> 42:21.000
when the number of costs is related to the number of produced products, and a long-term approach.

42:21.000 --> 42:28.000
That is, we need to increase the number of enterprises in order to produce more products.

42:28.000 --> 42:33.000
To build one enterprise, you need to spend several years,

42:33.000 --> 42:43.000
but every time the number of enterprises increases, so-called constant costs also increase.

42:43.000 --> 42:47.000
That is, in the long term, any costs are variable.

42:47.000 --> 42:57.000
All costs are variable, since all prices change, salaries change, prices for materials, services, everything changes.

42:57.000 --> 43:01.000
That is, in the long term, all costs are variable.

43:01.000 --> 43:13.000
Nevertheless, in the short term, we can divide the costs that are variable from the costs that are constant.

43:13.000 --> 43:20.000
Therefore, costs can be constant or fixed only in a limited period.

43:20.000 --> 43:26.000
That is, for the purpose of management, this is usually not more than one year.

43:26.000 --> 43:33.000
And during this one year, it is assumed that constant costs will be unchanged.

43:34.000 --> 43:37.000
An example of constant costs.

43:37.000 --> 43:45.000
A cannery manufacturer needs one master of change for an eight-hour shift.

43:45.000 --> 43:53.000
The volume of production can vary from 0 to 500,000 cans per month per shift.

43:53.000 --> 43:58.000
The salary of the master of change is 40,000 rubles per month.

43:58.000 --> 44:05.000
Again, I remind you that all prices and figures are conditional and are only given as an example.

44:05.000 --> 44:14.000
So, the range of production volume can vary from 0 to 500,000 cans.

44:15.000 --> 44:29.000
If we remember the variable costs, we know that the variable costs for each cannery will change proportionally.

44:29.000 --> 44:33.000
What happens to constant costs?

44:33.000 --> 44:36.000
Constant costs will be the same.

44:36.000 --> 44:44.000
Either we have 0 produced cans or 500,000 cans.

44:44.000 --> 44:47.000
That is, for one month, one shift.

44:47.000 --> 44:49.000
Per month, one shift.

44:49.000 --> 44:55.000
We see that constant costs do not depend on the volume of production.

44:55.000 --> 44:56.000
Why is that?

44:56.000 --> 45:01.000
Because the master of change receives 40,000 rubles per month.

45:01.000 --> 45:10.000
Regardless of whether he is on a constant rate and receives this salary, regardless of whether he was given an order or not.

45:10.000 --> 45:16.000
This is the essence of his contract with the employer.

45:16.000 --> 45:22.000
In any case, we must pay the master 40,000 rubles for work.

45:22.000 --> 45:28.000
Even if we have 1, 2 or more cans.

45:28.000 --> 45:33.000
At the same time, we will pay him the same amount if 500,000 cans are produced.

45:33.000 --> 45:39.000
What will happen if more than 500,000 cans are produced?

45:39.000 --> 45:43.000
He simply will not be able to control this volume of work.

45:43.000 --> 45:48.000
Therefore, we must hire another master of change.

45:48.000 --> 45:53.000
And we must also set up another shift.

45:53.000 --> 45:55.000
That is, what happens?

45:55.000 --> 45:57.000
500,000 cans.

45:57.000 --> 46:04.000
Up to 500,000 cans, we will have the same salary of the master of change.

46:04.000 --> 46:11.000
But if we have 500,000 and 10 cans, and we set up a new shift,

46:11.000 --> 46:18.000
even if in the second shift he only released 10 cans, he will still have to pay 40,000 rubles.

46:18.000 --> 46:26.000
If he produces the same 500,000 cans,

46:26.000 --> 46:31.000
that is, we will have a million cans produced in two shifts in a month,

46:31.000 --> 46:40.000
we see that we will pay the same 40,000 rubles plus 40,000 rubles, 80,000 rubles per month for two masters.

46:40.000 --> 46:49.000
This is what is called constant costs within a certain range.

46:49.000 --> 46:51.000
What is the range?

46:51.000 --> 46:54.000
The range is from 0 to 500,000.

46:54.000 --> 46:58.000
The next range is from 500,000 to a million.

46:58.000 --> 47:00.000
What will happen next?

47:00.000 --> 47:04.000
If we need to produce more than a million cans,

47:04.000 --> 47:15.000
we hire a third master, and in three shifts the plant will produce 500,000 cans,

47:15.000 --> 47:19.000
500,000 cans per shift, a million in two shifts.

47:19.000 --> 47:25.000
And now let's think about what will happen if we need more than a million and a half cans.

47:25.000 --> 47:27.000
Three shifts are already taken.

47:27.000 --> 47:38.000
We can't increase the number of cans produced from aluminum by hiring a third master.

47:38.000 --> 47:46.000
We need to place the production on a new production area,

47:46.000 --> 47:50.000
open an additional workshop, maybe open an additional plant.

47:51.000 --> 47:58.000
This is the concept of the range and the concept of constant costs.

47:58.000 --> 48:00.000
Let's summarize.

48:00.000 --> 48:11.000
We see a table with the number of cans per month and the total salary of shift masters per month in rubles.

48:11.000 --> 48:19.000
That is, from 0 to 500,000 cans, the salary of shift masters will be 40,000 rubles,

48:19.000 --> 48:24.000
and from 500,000 to a million, 80,000.

48:24.000 --> 48:33.000
If another shift is added, new constant costs remain constant within the new range.

48:33.000 --> 48:40.000
Constant costs per unit of production change in the opposite dependency on the volume of production,

48:40.000 --> 48:47.000
that is, with the increase in the volume of production, constant costs per unit decrease.

48:47.000 --> 48:50.000
Now let's see how this happens.

48:50.000 --> 49:00.000
In this table we see the volume of production in pieces, cans, and costs per unit of production,

49:00.000 --> 49:02.000
that is, costs per can.

49:04.000 --> 49:08.000
100,000 cans.

49:08.000 --> 49:16.000
We divide 40,000 rubles, the salary of the shift master, into 100,000 cans,

49:16.000 --> 49:21.000
and we have costs per unit of production of 40 kopecks.

49:21.000 --> 49:34.000
With 300,000 cans, 40,000 is divided by 300,000 and we get 13.3 kopecks per can.

49:34.000 --> 49:43.000
With 500,000 cans, 40,000 is divided by 500,000 and we get 8 kopecks per can.

49:43.000 --> 49:56.000
With 600,000, we divide 40,000 by 600,000 and we get 1.03 kopecks.

49:57.000 --> 50:03.000
With 600,000 cans, the volume of production is higher than the volume of predictability,

50:03.000 --> 50:10.000
which means that another shift must be added and another shift master hired.

50:10.000 --> 50:18.000
Now let's look at the table where the dependence of the volume of production of cans in pieces

50:19.000 --> 50:22.000
and the costs per unit of production in rubles are shown.

50:22.000 --> 50:34.000
That is, how much does one can cost when we divide the salary of the shift master into the number of cans.

50:34.000 --> 50:42.000
With 100,000 cans, we see 40,000 divided by 100,000 and we get 40 kopecks.

50:42.000 --> 50:50.000
With 300,000 cans, 40,000 is divided by 300,000 and we get 13.3 kopecks.

50:50.000 --> 50:58.000
With 500,000 cans, 40,000 is divided by 500,000 and we see 8 kopecks.

50:58.000 --> 51:02.000
With 600,000, what can we expect?

51:02.000 --> 51:07.000
We can expect that the cost per can will decrease.

51:07.000 --> 51:13.000
Indeed, we divide 40,000 by 600,000, but what happens?

51:13.000 --> 51:21.000
It turns out that we no longer need to divide 40,000, but 80,000,

51:21.000 --> 51:26.000
because we will have one shift added.

51:26.000 --> 51:33.000
That is, it turns out that we will have 13 kopecks again.

51:34.000 --> 51:41.000
That is, with the production of 600,000 cans, the volume of production is higher than the predictability range,

51:41.000 --> 51:48.000
which means that another shift should be added and another shift master should be hired.

51:48.000 --> 51:54.000
And now, from the analysis of the separateness of constant and variable costs,

51:54.000 --> 51:58.000
we will move on to the analysis of the point of cost-payment.

51:58.000 --> 52:09.000
The task is to determine the point of cost-payment and use the marginal profit to determine the point of cost-payment.

52:09.000 --> 52:17.000
The analysis of the point of cost-payment uses the basic elements of the analysis of the cost-payment volume

52:17.000 --> 52:21.000
to determine the point of cost-payment.

52:21.000 --> 52:30.000
That is, we see that this type of analysis is called the analysis of the cost-payment volume.

52:30.000 --> 52:35.000
What is required for the analysis of the point of cost-payment?

52:35.000 --> 52:38.000
What are the prerequisites?

52:38.000 --> 52:42.000
First, the income is equal to the total cost.

52:42.000 --> 52:47.000
When the income is equal to the total cost, what do we get?

52:47.000 --> 52:52.000
We will not have a profit, but we will not have a loss.

52:52.000 --> 52:57.000
And only after that does the company begin to receive a profit.

52:57.000 --> 53:02.000
The next term is the safety margin.

53:02.000 --> 53:09.000
Under the safety margin, the number of units sold or the volume of sales in rubles is understood,

53:09.000 --> 53:16.000
with which actual sales may fall below planned sales without loss for the company.

53:19.000 --> 53:26.000
Let's see what the general equation for calculating the point of cost-payment will look like.

53:26.000 --> 53:36.000
We use Latin denominations to denote the necessary elements of this equation.

53:36.000 --> 53:42.000
These denominations are common all over the world, so we can use them.

53:42.000 --> 53:50.000
Sales are denoted by the letter S, which corresponds to the English word sales.

53:50.000 --> 53:58.000
Variable costs are denoted by the Latin letters V and C, which means variable costs.

53:58.000 --> 54:06.000
Constant costs are denoted by the Latin letters F and C, which means fixed costs.

54:06.000 --> 54:13.000
Sales minus variable costs minus constant costs are equal to zero.

54:13.000 --> 54:18.000
This is the general equation for calculating the point of cost-payment.

54:18.000 --> 54:20.000
We see it.

54:20.000 --> 54:26.000
S minus VC minus FC is equal to zero.

54:26.000 --> 54:42.000
Sales minus variable costs minus fixed costs is equal to zero.

54:44.000 --> 54:54.000
For example, a company with a limited liability, Metal Product, produces decorative cast-iron stands.

54:54.000 --> 55:00.000
Variable costs are equal to 500 rubles for a cast-iron stand.

55:00.000 --> 55:04.000
Constant costs are on average 200,000 rubles per year.

55:04.000 --> 55:08.000
Each stand is sold for 900 rubles.

55:08.000 --> 55:19.000
The task is to calculate the point of cost-payment for stands in units of sales, where X is the number of units of sales.

55:20.000 --> 55:26.000
We use the formula we just analyzed.

55:26.000 --> 55:32.000
S minus VC minus FC is equal to zero.

55:32.000 --> 55:39.000
Sales minus variable costs minus constant costs is equal to zero.

55:40.000 --> 55:50.000
If we substitute 900 times X instead of S, what is 900 times X?

55:50.000 --> 55:55.000
Each stand is sold for 900 rubles.

55:55.000 --> 55:58.000
X is the number of units of sales.

55:58.000 --> 56:07.000
900 times X is the number of units of sales.

56:07.000 --> 56:11.000
900 times X minus 500 times X.

56:11.000 --> 56:14.000
X is the number of units of sales.

56:14.000 --> 56:19.000
500 times X is the number of variable costs.

56:19.000 --> 56:26.000
Minus 200 times X is the number of constant costs.

56:26.000 --> 56:35.000
So, in this equation, 900 times X minus 500 times X minus 200,000 is equal to zero.

56:37.000 --> 56:42.000
First, we calculate the point of cost-payment in units.

56:43.000 --> 56:46.000
X is equal to 500 units.

56:48.000 --> 56:53.000
Let's go back and remember how we get this figure.

56:53.000 --> 56:56.000
900 minus 500 times X.

56:56.000 --> 57:05.000
If we calculate X, we get 900 minus 500 is equal to 400.

57:05.000 --> 57:09.000
So, we get 400 times X minus 200,000.

57:09.000 --> 57:12.000
Or 400 times X is equal to 200,000.

57:12.000 --> 57:18.000
To calculate X, we divide 200,000 by 400.

57:18.000 --> 57:24.000
Thus, X is equal to 500 units.

57:28.000 --> 57:31.000
400 times X is equal to 200,000.

57:31.000 --> 57:34.000
X is equal to 500 units.

57:34.000 --> 57:40.000
Next, we calculate the point of cost-payment in rubles.

57:40.000 --> 57:46.000
We multiply 900 by 500.

57:46.000 --> 57:49.000
What is 900?

57:49.000 --> 57:54.000
900 is the price of one stand.

57:54.000 --> 58:01.000
